observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the account and make the necessary adjustments immediately, and;

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to ensure timely reconciliation of cashbook balances and accounting records before closing the book on year-end.

Enjoin concerned personnel to exert efforts to collect the receivables by sending collection letters to the principal debtors and/or co-makers; 

Enforce the conditions of loan repayment as well as the penalty provision in case of default in payment, if applicable; and

Propose a payment scheme that are amenable to debtors in order to enforce collection of receivables especially from debtors who are still transacting with the LGU.

Create a centralized Property/Supply Unit or GSO to handle the monitoring of request and/or distribution of property or supply to end-users;

Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to adopt in full the Perpetual Inventory Method in his recording of inventories;

Require the Office of the Municipal Treasurer and the Office of the Municipal Accountant to prioritize the reconciliation between the supplies and materials expenses accounts per books and SSMI;

Require the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to include in the SSMI the unutilized inventory accounts of the previous year but are consumed/ utilized in the current year; and,

Require the concerned officers to maintain stock cards and supplies ledger cards for each item of Inventory to ensure proper accounting and promote better control in the receipt and issuance of supplies.

Enjoin the Inventory Committee, headed by the Municipal Treasurer, and the Municipal Accountant to identify the cause of the variance between the physically counted movable properties and the Accounting records and reconcile them; 

Create a committee composed of one personnel each from the Treasurer’s Office and Accounting Office who shall reconcile their respective records of PPE on a full- time basis and at the same time maintain updated and complete PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards; 

For the local road networks, enjoin the Municipal Engineer to conduct an investigation on the existence of the uncounted local road networks and forward the result to the Municipal Accountant; and,

If warranted, enjoin the Municipal Accountant to request for derecognition of the local road networks that have already been reblocked.

We recommended that Management enjoin the Disposal Committee to expedite the actual disposal of the unserviceable properties;

Assign personnel to locate/account the missing or non-existing items noted during the inventory taking or trace the documents of previous years to serve as reference to identify the accountable persons for the lost properties, investigate whether there is a need to demand settlement from the accountable persons and/or submit request for relief from accountability; and 

If warranted, facilitate the process of disposition and derecognition in the books following the guidelines and provisions of applicable COA Circulars.

Ensure proper planning of projects, implement quality check-ups/inspections, and intensify monitoring of all infrastructure projects by the Municipality to minimize defects and avoid deficiencies; 

Direct the Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the Contractor to fix the thermal cracks on the road to prevent further deterioration as soon as possible; and,

Strictly comply with the provisions stated in Section 2 of PD 1445 and 62.2.2 of the Revised IRR of RA9184.

Municipal Treasurer to immediately return the unutilized funds to the NGAs concerned or request for the appropriate authority to use said funds;

Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary journal entry to correct the negative balance of Due to NGAs; and,

Confirm the status of the balances under the Due to NGAs account from the Source Agencies and the legal basis for maintaining the same in the Special Trust Fund accounts.

Enjoin concerned personnel to exert efforts to collect the receivables by sending collection letters to the principal debtors and/or co-makers; 

Propose payment scheme that would be applicable to the current financial situation of the debtors/ borrowers;

In case of deceased debtor(s), request assistance from the members of the family of dead beneficiary(ies) with outstanding loan to secure the death certificate to support the request for write-off; and 

After securing the death certificate, file the request for write-off on the dormant loans of dead beneficiary(ies) pursuant to Section 8 of COA Circular No. 2016-005.

Municipal Treasurer to secure confirmation from the Government Service Insurance Services (GSIS) the list of employees whose contributions were not remitted; 

Municipal Accountant to trace from their records the listings of the employees from whom the total of ₱426,520.72 contributions were withheld; and finally

Municipal Accountant to prepare thereafter the necessary documents for the remittance of said amount to GSIS.

We recommended that Management enjoin the Municipal Accountant to:

conduct periodic reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts in order to identify possible errors/adjustments which need to be recorded in the books;

trace the difference of ₱4,321,307.64 existing between the Due from Other Funds and Due to Other Funds accounts to show a reconciled amount in the financial statements;

present proof of the items already traced; and

adjust in the books, if warranted.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the:

desist from using the undeposited collections to pay for various expenses;

closely monitor the daily collections and remittances from all collectors/tellers and ensure that all collections are properly accounted for and deposited promptly and intact as prescribed under COA Circular No. 92-382 and Section 32, Chapter 3 of the NGAS Manual for Local Government Units Volume I.

We recommended and Management agreed to direct the: 

Municipal Accountant to effect immediately, the recording of the appropriate adjusting journal entries by considering the necessary supporting documents and computations, if any, as bases in preparing the adjusting journal entries, in conformity with Section 3.3 of COA Circular No. 96-011;

Municipal Treasurer to immediately submit the unrecorded check disbursements to the Office of the Municipal Accountant.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

Require the Municipal Assessor’s Office to facilitate the registration of the untitled land and/or transfer of title of the aforementioned parcels of lots in the name of the LGU with the Registry of Deeds;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer as the Property Custodian to maintain updated report of the LGU’s properties.

strategically plan the allocation of budget to identified Barangays under one project classification to ensure that the implementation of the same is fully realized;

closely coordinate with other funding agencies to avoid allocating funds to projects already funded by these agencies; and

prioritize projects so that the more urgent ones may be allocated sufficient funds rather than spread the fund to several projects which eventually will not be implemented/will not be completed because of insufficiency of funds.

re-establish and reinforce the deputation of barangay officials to aid the LGU in collecting taxes by setting their specific functions and responsibilities;

create new positions and provide capable personnel that will be in-charge with the issuance of Notice of Delinquency and the monitoring of the delinquent taxpayers; and

intensify the tax campaign by sending treasury personnel to barangay especially during barangay assemblies for tax information drive in order to invite more taxpayers to pay taxes on time.

Require the concerned personnel to adhere to the general process for Inventory control;


Create a centralized Property/Supply Unit or GSO to handle the monitoring of request and/or distribution of property or supply to end-users;

Require the Accountant and GSO to regularly maintain and update the SLC and SC, respectively;

Require inspection of supplies and materials used by end-users before issuance of RIS to control the frequency and volume of purchase requests;

Require the end-users to consolidate the RIS weekly in the SSMI and regularly submit the same to the GSO; and

Require the GSO to regularly submit the same to the Accountant in order for the latter to prepare a JEV to recognize the issuance.

Conduct physical count of the local road networks and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;

Prepare the Report on Local Road Networks, maintain local road inventory, road map and property cards for all roads and its component;



Maintain subsidiary ledger cards for roads and road components of every road network and prepare lapsing schedule showing the computation of the depreciation of each component of the Road Network System account;

Disclose the total Road Network System account in the Notes to Financial Statements and make adjusting entry regarding depreciation and derecognition of the replaced asset following the provision of COA Circular 2015-008; and

Provide a complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

Designate Property/Supply Unit staff to oversee monitoring of procured DRRM items;

Require Property/Supply Unit staff to prepare Inventory List of all DRRM items, including PPEs and Supplies; and

Submit monthly Report of Supplies and Material Issued (RSMI) to Accounting unit for recording in the books.

